### Event Handling > Pointer capture

Source: https://github.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/blob/master/docs/API/events.mdx

In React Three Fiber, pointer capture behaves differently than in the standard DOM. While the DOM replaces the hit test with the capturing object, Fiber adds the capturing object to the hit test result. If the capturing object was not hit, all hit objects and their ancestors receive the event first, followed by the capturing object. You can use event.stopPropagation() on the capturing object to ensure that objects that were actually hit receive pointerout events. Note that setPointerCapture and releasePointerCapture are accessed via event.target rather than directly on Object3D instances.

